For interaction category events only. This is the total time for the interaction to render on the device. In addition to render time, this usually includes all external calls associated with the interaction.  Currently, this attribute is measured in seconds for Android devices and in milliseconds for iOS devices.

For interaction category events only. This is the label of the interaction associated with the event. It is by default assigned by New Relic.  For example: ApplicationsListFragment or Display iOS_Example.MasterViewController.
For interaction category events only. The UTC based timestamp for when the event was sent to New Relic. This is different from the attribute ‘timestamp’, which is when the event began.
The processor architecture of the device. For example: armv7 or arm64.

For an HTTP response, the data type of the returned response. For example: `text/html` or `application/json`.
Indicates whether this event was sampled for inclusion in a distributed trace. Only present when distributed tracing is enabled.
A measure of "thread utilization", representing the number of threads handling concurrent requests.
The start time of the job in epoch milliseconds.
Links all New Relic trace data (events, etc.) within the call chain together. Included when Distributed Tracing is enabled.
Name of the transaction in which the error occurred. For example: `Controller/customers/show`. Value may be `Unknown` if error occurs outside of a transaction.
The UI display name equivalent of transactionName.
The New Relic event type. For example: `Transaction` or `Span`.
(Python agent only) The number of calls to read() by the WSGI server to handle request.
(Python agent only) The number of calls to readline() by the WSGI server to handle request.
(Python agent only) The number of calls to readlines() by the WSGI server to handle request.
(Python agent only) Number of calls to yield by the WSGI server to send response.
(Python agent only) Number of calls to yield by the WSGI server to send response.
